                  CENTURY.” live from her television show on 17 April 2009, with
                  Twitter CEO Ev Williams watching on. The effect was immediate:
                  account sign-ups to the platform spiked, and the Twitter
                  userbase grew rapidly from then on. Although attracting more
                  than 320 million monthly active users during its heyday
                  (Molina), Twitter was never a mass participation platform
                  comparable to Facebook, Weibo, or Instagram. Instead, what
                  distinguished it from its competition was both the
                  particularly influential clientele of local, domestic, and
                  international actors that it was able to attract (e.g.
                  Ausserhofer \& Maireder), and the way in which its flat and
                  open platform affordances and network structure at least
                  appeared to (and in some cases genuinely did) enable direct
                  interaction between these elite accounts and the larger mass
                  of ordinary users. While never consciously designed for this
                  purpose (cf. Burgess \& Baym), once it was fully established,
                  Twitter provided direct access to the posts of a collection of
                  celebrities, politicians, journalists, business leaders,
                  experts, activists, government and non-government
                  institutions, and corporations that was often nearly complete
                  in many of the regions in which the platform was being used.
                  This also led to it becoming a platform of critical importance
                  for sharing, discussing, and otherwise engaging with news and
                  current events. The substantial changes to Twitter as a
                  company and platform since its takeover by Elon Musk on 27
                  October 2022 have meant that that platform has died, however.
                  Even the name Twitter itself no longer exists, following its
                  rebrand as ‘X’. This article explores how these changes have
                  affected opportunities for constructive, prosocial online
                  public debate, and examines the extent to which new social
                  platforms are able to fill the space now vacated by Twitter.
                  News, Public Debate, and Prosocial Activism on Twitter The use
                  of Twitter for engagement with news and current events has
                  perhaps been highlighted most prominently in early scholarly
                  analyses of the platform: such work addressed, for example,
                  the role of Twitter in crisis communication during natural
                  disasters and political events (Hughes \& Palen), or more
                  generally described the platform as an ‘ambient news’ network
                  (Hermida). Again, the flat and open structure of the platform
                  – where the vast majority of accounts and their posts were
                  publicly accessible by default; and where users could freely
                  follow and tweet at almost any other account, without a need
                  to be accepted as a follower or ‘friend’ (Gruzd et al.) –
                  played a critical role in facilitating such uses, as did the
                  rapidly growing use of hashtags as a user-generated means of
                  coordinating feeds of posts relating to a given topic.
                  Hashtags proved especially critical, indeed, to the bottom-up
                  surfacing of information without the (initial) involvement of
                  major institutional accounts. They enabled key voices to be
                  “crowdsourced to prominence through the pluralizing practices
                  of retweeting, mentioning, and other addressivity markers” by
                  the platform’s ordinary users, as Meraz \& Papacharissi have
                  put it (158). In spite of these important uses, Twitter was
                  always more than ‘only’ a news network, however, as Burgess \&
                  Baym have documented. Beyond their uses in breaking news (and
                  sometimes overlapping with such uses), for instance, hashtags
                  have always also been crucial to connecting communities – from
                  small and localised interest and identity groups to major,
                  global, prosocial activism like \#metoo and \#blacklivesmatter
                  (e.g. Jackson \& Foucault Welles). In doing so, well beyond
                  their roles in the context of acute events, they also served a
                  purpose in facilitating the longer-term tracking of issues and
                  events. This is demonstrated for example by the six-year
                  campaign in Australia for a Royal Commission of Inquiry into
                  the federal government’s illegal \#Robodebt scheme (Dehghan \&
                  Bruns). The platform facilitated what Bennett \& Segerberg
                  have described as “connective action”, enabling the ad hoc
                  organisation of hashtag followers into crowds with a notable
                  impact on public debate (though not necessarily public policy)
                  related to the issues that such connective action addressed.
                  Through such efforts, as well as more day-to-day thematic
                  attention and networking between accounts focussing on related
                  issues, Twitter also enabled the emergence of a new class of
                  expert voices, community leaders, and issue influencers. This
                  use of social media to build and exert influence was certainly
                  not limited to Twitter alone (Abidin), and of course also
                  produced a substantial amount of ill-informed charlatans
                  opining on topics well outside their area of expertise. But
                  yet again the very public and open nature of communication on
                  Twitter often also served to flush out such misinformation, as
                  genuine experts responded to and debunked misguided views – at
                  least as long as the operators of the Twitter platform also
                  played their part by acting on reports of influence operations
                  and egregious mis- and disinformation sharing. Genuine experts
                  and community leaders found an audience on Twitter, then,
                  especially also because its flat and open structure enabled
                  the rapid horizontal dissemination of their posts not only
                  through hashtagging, but (arguably more importantly) also with
                  the help of retweets (Hemsley). Retweeting distributed other
                  accounts’ tweets to the retweeting user’s network of
                  followers, even if they were not themselves following the
                  retweeted user or any hashtags included in that users’ tweets
                  (cf. Bruns \& Moe). This substantially aided the serendipitous
                  discovery of emerging, novel, and unexpected topics and
                  events, and was itself amplified further by the Twitter
                  platform’s identification of current ‘trending topics’,
                  globally or in a user’s geographic region. In a refrain that
                  is recurring throughout Twitter’s history (also cf. Burgess \&
                  Baym), Twitter as a platform worked best when its systems
                  responded to the interests and practices of its userbase. Such
                  serendipitous, playful, and social – indeed, joyful – uses of
                  the platform were often overshadowed by the considerable media
                  and scholarly interest in Twitter’s more serious news and
                  business uses. Yet the evidence suggests that social, phatic
                  uses (from simply hanging out online together to mostly
                  good-natured shitposting) accounted for the majority of
                  Twitter activity on any given day (Bruns \& Moon). For all the
                  cultural cachet that the hashtag has gained as a media object
                  well beyond Twitter itself, hashtagged tweets were always only
                  a minor subset of all tweets, for instance, and the vast
                  majority of ordinary users did not engage with the platform
                  predominantly for professional purposes. As David Roth put it
                  in one of the many eulogies for the Twitter that was which
                  have been written since the Musk takeover, then, for all the
                  overwrought ways in which Twitter has been described—[Tucker]
                  Carlson called it “the place where our national conversation
                  incubates and develops”…—the comparison that always made the
                  most sense was too small-bore for the big-thinking types. I’ve
                  always thought of Twitter as a house party that I could visit
                  or leave at my leisure. Different things were happening in
                  different rooms, some of them for me and some of them very
                  much not. Over time I learned how to find the scenes and
                  conversations I liked, and came to recognize the people I saw
                  in those rooms as friends. (The owners were of course not
                  around.) This is a fine thing for a website to be, I think.
                  This seems to encapsulate well the general sense of loss that
                  many long-term Twitter users have experienced since the
                  inexorable decline of the platform set in after Elon Musk
                  bought it – yet (like other memories of adolescent house
                  parties) it also creates an image of an antediluvian golden
                  age that likely never existed as such. The Writing on the Wall
                  The sober truth is that Twitter was never well-managed. The
                  owners were indeed never around, or, even if they were,
                  usually failed to show unwanted intruders the door. During its
                  early days, this inattention was perhaps masked by an overall
                  sense of excitement and enthusiasm for this new platform, and
                  by the way management seemed to both take on new ideas (search
                  functions, hashtags, etc.) and open the platform’s technical
                  infrastructure to developers, businesses, and researchers to
                  build third-party tools and extensions and to better
                  understand how people were using the platform (Burgess \&
                  Bruns). As Ash notes, even Twitter’s 2013 statement to the US
                  Securities and Exchange Commission in preparation for its
                  public listing on the stock exchange still makes the
                  commitment that the mission we serve as Twitter, Inc. is to
                  give everyone the power to create and share ideas and
                  information instantly without barriers. Our business and
                  revenue will always follow that mission in ways to improve –
                  and not detract from – a free and global conversation.
                  (Twitter, Inc.) This commitment waned considerably as
                  Twitter’s management, in search of a longer-term business
                  plan, began to crack down on third-party uses of its data, and
                  sought to monetise such data for themselves – not least also
                  in response to shareholder pressure to perform financially. By
                  2015, “no longer is Twitter speaking to barriers of freedom,
                  but rather, they focus on generating revenue. A marked shift
                  in rhetoric is now made visible” in its quarterly earnings
                  reports (Ash), especially as Twitter’s development slowed
                  while the company invested in ill-fated ventures like video
                  platforms Vine and Periscope that sought to expand to new
                  userbases rather than serve existing users (cf. Scolari).
                  Poorly thought-through and widely opposed decisions such as
                  the redesign of the ‘star’ button (as a form of bookmarking
                  tweets) to a ‘heart’, implying emotional attachment (Bucher \&
                  Helmond), and stubborn inaction in the face of user demand –
                  exemplified most obviously by the company’s notorious refusal
                  to introduce any, even limited, functionality to edit tweets
                  after posting (Martineau) – were signs of further trouble to
                  come. Some such trouble also originated externally, not least
                  in the growth in coordinated influence operations designed to
                  affect public opinion for instance in the 2016 Brexit
                  referendum and U.S. presidential election (Bastos; Golovchenko
                  et al.), and the rapid rise in abuse and hate speech
                  especially in the wake of Donald Trump’s election. Not only
                  did Twitter management appear to do too little, too late: some
                  of its inaction seemed to stem from a misguided,
                  pseudo-libertarian valuation of unconstrained ‘free speech’
                  above all else, and/or a concern for the business and
                  political implications of acting more forcefully against mis-
                  and disinformation, abuse, hate speech, and other obvious
                  ills. Twitter’s status as Trump’s favourite platform was good
                  for business and brand recognition in the short term, in other
                  words, no matter the long-term damage that platforming Trump
                  and other high-volume sources of blatant disinformation and
                  hate speech might also cause for both company and community.
                  It is notable in this context that, but for a handful of
                  high-profile and at times poorly handled collaborations (cf.
                  Liao), Twitter largely also failed to engage with the
                  substantial volume of leading scholarship on prosocial as well
                  as problematic user practices that its earlier, more
                  permissive collaboration settings had encouraged. Especially
                  after 2016, substantial computational social science
                  scholarship addressed the challenges of identifying and
                  combatting mis- and disinformation operations (e.g. Kim et
                  al.; Starbird et al.) and other forms of what Facebook came to
                  call ‘coordinated inauthentic behaviour’ (Gleicher), while
                  other researchers dissected the company’s use of appeals to
                  ‘free speech’ as a justification for its continued platforming
                  of outright fascists (Konikoff), yet Twitter’s leadership
                  largely ignored any of this work. It also actively frustrated
                  its user community’s attempts to rekindle the DIY spirit of
                  the platform’s early days and develop communal approaches to
                  combatting problematic actors, for instance by creating
                  collaborative blocklists (Geiger). It was only towards the end
                  of this late period in Twitter’s pre-Musk trajectory that the
                  company appeared to rethink its relationship especially with
                  researchers (and it is possible that this volte face was
                  prompted to some extent by the coming Digital Services Act in
                  the European Union, with its requirements for Very Large
                  Online Platforms to provide better data access to
                  researchers). In 2021, Twitter introduced a powerful new
                  Application Programming Interface specifically dedicated to
                  research purposes (Perez, “Twitter”), as well as a no-code
                  Tweet Downloader functionality that would provide datasets
                  directly in human-readable file formats without the need for
                  any programming. These genuinely useful facilities would soon
                  be dismantled again, however, as Twitter’s fortunes changed
                  irrevocably following its acquisition by Elon Musk in 2022
                  (Stokel-Walker). Their brief flourishing serves as a reminder
                  of a better path not taken. The Decline of Online Public
                  Debate Open, prosocial, constructive public debate flourished
                  briefly in online spaces such as Twitter during the first half
                  of the 2010s. This substantially aided phenomena such as the
                  Arab Spring, Me Too, and Black Lives Matter, as well as
                  countless smaller and more localised societal movements. Those
                  last two examples also point to the fact that these
                  developments were never truly global, however: they occurred
                  predominantly in the democratic countries of the Global North,
                  while similar developments elsewhere were often snuffed out by
                  more repressive regimes, at times even with the help of
                  Twitter and other platforms that acquiesced all too easily to
                  the take-down demands made by such governments. Available
                  space in this article does not permit a full discussion of
                  Twitter’s use across the diverse political contexts of the
                  Majority World. Twitter was used to pursue social change,
                  protest government oppression, and organise resistance against
                  authoritarian regimes in a broad range of contexts: for
                  instance, activism in Indonesia towards the criminalisation of
                  sexual violence (Azmi); resistance against government
                  repression of public debate in Saudi Arabia (Uniacke);
                  diasporic opposition against autocratic leaders in Russia and
                  Iran (Dehghan and Glazunova). The temporary success of protest
                  campaigns and movements, from the Arab Spring onwards, in
                  attracting a global audience to their cause was aided not
                  least by the deployment of singular hashtags to bundle and
                  amplify critical information and calls to action – but it
                  increasingly also produced a two-fold backlash from contrarian
                  actors. On the one hand, it indicated a pressing need to
                  develop effective countermeasures against the influence of
                  such campaigns, while on the other, it pointed to the
                  potential of instrumentalising these same processes in support
                  of far more reactionary and disruptive purposes. While earlier
                  examples can readily be identified, too, the second half of
                  the 2010s is widely seen as the period during which these
                  efforts produced their first major harvest. Much as earlier
                  prosocial campaigns had attracted and enrolled a public
                  yearning for change, now domestic influence campaigns in the
                  United States, the United Kingdom, and elsewhere – potentially
                  assisted by the Russian ‘Internet Research Agency’ troll farm
                  (Bail et al.) and other foreign actors – engaged the partisan
                  supporters of reactionary and populist causes in what Starbird
                  et al. came to call “participatory disinformation”. Through a
                  mixture of genuine influencers, inauthentic accounts, and
                  bots, they gave ordinary partisans licence to push false
                  narratives that supported their own side and distracted or
                  denigrated their opponents. If nothing else, the sheer volume
                  of content produced by such efforts – whether by the Russian
                  ‘Internet Research Agency’, the Saudi regime’s ‘troll army’
                  (Benner et al.), or Indonesian political parties’ extensive
                  cohorts of ‘buzzers’ (Burgess \& Souisa) – was often already
                  sufficient to overwhelm any meaningful discussion that might
                  otherwise have occurred in the communicative spaces Twitter
                  provided. Public debate ahead of the Brexit referendum and the
                  first election of Donald Trump to the U.S. presidency in 2016
                  was undermined in this way, and similar patterns of
                  disinformation, division, and decoherence are observable for
                  most major public debates – in the Global North and the
                  Majority World – since then, especially perhaps for debates
                  about climate action and responses to the COVID-19 pandemic
                  (Graham \& FitzGerald, “Exploring”). This backlash against the
                  potential prosocial uses of Twitter and other social media
                  platforms for genuine public debate amongst a set of actors
                  well beyond the elite that populate the “virtual stage of
                  mediated communication” provided by the classic Habermasian
                  public sphere (Habermas) was entirely foreseeable, perhaps. It
                  represents only the latest, social media-enhanced iteration of
                  the “fear, uncertainty, and doubt” playbook supposedly first
                  used by IBM to denigrate its competitors in the 1970s – an
                  approach which by now is so well established it has even earnt
                  a standing acronym in marketing research: FUD (Pfaffenberger).
                  Its major innovation is simply to capitalise on the very
                  affordances of social media platforms such as Twitter to
                  institute a participatory FUD campaign, where the polarising
                  and divisive messages produced by authentic and inauthentic
                  influencers are now willingly spread online by partisans
                  themselves. Indeed, in doing so, it revives the classic Soviet
                  communication strategy of agit-prop – agitation and
                  propagation – for a new communicative environment (Svegaard).
                  Yet foreseeable or not, this instrumentalisation of platform
                  affordances against societal cohesion turned out to be
                  difficult to defend against – especially also because the
                  extreme ‘free speech’ positions embraced by Twitter and other
                  platform operators. Their resistance against well-intentioned
                  regulatory interventions by democratic government authorities,
                  their belligerence towards independent, critical,
                  public-interest research, and their dismissal of their own
                  user communities’ requests for more proactive interventions
                  against disruptive and inauthentic accounts shut off many of
                  the possible avenues that could have been taken in the fight
                  against those reactionary groups which sought to undermine
                  meaningful online public debate. Notoriously, for instance,
                  Twitter CEO Jack Dorsey reluctantly sanctioned the take-down
                  of Donald Trump’s account only after the latter had encouraged
                  the violent insurrection against the legitimate U.S. election
                  certification process on 6 January 2021 (Paul, “Twitter”).
                  Viewed with the benefit of hindsight, it is clear that such
                  naïve inaction materially aided these disruptive actors’
                  efforts to undermine online public debate and further damage
                  societal cohesion. Platforms and platform regulators failed,
                  and still fail, to adequately protect the public from those
                  who seek to disinform and divide for base political reasons.
                  It is bitterly ironic in this context both that Twitter’s
                  failure to act against those who sought to undermine it – and
                  here, especially against inauthentic bot accounts – in turn
                  also became a key issue in Elon Musk’s efforts to acquire the
                  platform (Milmo), and that Musk’s own dismantling of any even
                  rudimentary defences against coordinated inauthentic
                  intrusions has subsequently led to the rebranded X becoming
                  overwhelmed with newly created bot accounts (Graham \&
                  FitzGerald, Bots). Online Public Debate beyond Twitter Such
                  growing dysfunction in online public debate is not, and never
                  was, limited to Twitter alone, of course. Meta and Alphabet
                  (as owners of platforms such as Facebook, Instagram, WhatsApp,
                  and YouTube) have been similarly culpable for their negligence
                  in protecting their users from abuse and disinformation, and
                  for their opposition to legitimate democratic governments’
                  regulatory initiatives requiring them to do so. However,
                  Twitter’s unique – flat and open – structure of public
                  communication has meant that it came to occupy a special place
                  in the social media ecology, even in spite of its considerably
                  smaller userbase. When news broke of natural disasters,
                  political scandals, violent conflicts, scientific
                  breakthroughs, celebrity deaths, or other major developments,
                  people flocked to Twitter and not those other platforms. When
                  campaigns sought public visibility, community involvement, and
                  crowdsourced amplification, they did so on Twitter. When
                  citizens tried to get journalists to pay attention to emerging
                  issues, convince corporations to improve their practices, or
                  encourage politicians to change their views, they addressed
                  them on Twitter. This positioning is still well removed from
                  Twitter’s occasional self-aggrandisement as “the digital town
                  square” (Burgess), but it does mark Twitter as a distinct
                  place where public debate was likely to take place in a way
                  that it could not on platforms like Facebook, Instagram, and
                  WhatsApp (because debate there is not predominantly public),
                  nor on YouTube or TikTok (because their affordances privilege
                  the posting of public content rather than extensive and
                  ongoing debate). Town square or not, Twitter’s pre-Musk
                  management allowed this public space to atrophy through its
                  pursuit of profit over community, and its inattention to the
                  growing encroachment of disruptive and divisive forces. Its
                  various platform interventions, often strongly opposed by the
                  user community, represent what Cory Doctorow has described as
                  the “enshittification” of a platform for commercial gain. For
                  instance, Twitter’s 2016 transition from a simply
                  chronological to an algorithmically curated default activity
                  feed – which was subsequently found to privilege right-wing
                  politics (Huszár et al.) – maximised content visibility for
                  major accounts over ambient awareness of updates from those
                  accounts users had chosen to follow and interact with. This
                  constitutes a clear turn away from the mission “to give
                  everyone the power to create and share ideas and information
                  instantly without barriers” (Twitter, Inc.). Under Elon Musk,
                  as enshittification turned into enxittification and X
                  transformed altogether into a fascist hangout, the speed of
                  decline increased substantially. The algorithm was tweaked
                  further, not least to promote Musk’s own tweets regardless of
                  whether users were following him or not (Paul, “Elon Musk”).
                  Status as a major, verified account with Twitter’s previously
                  prestigious ‘blue tick’ was now for sale for as low as US\$8
                  (Mogyoros). And far-right accounts exploiting these new
                  realities to push disinformation and abusive content were even
                  rewarded with a share of X’s (dwindling) advertising revenue
                  (Lorenz). In response, a growing number of alternative
                  platform options have sought to position themselves as more or
                  less seamless replacements. These include Mastodon, with its
                  decentralised and federated network of bespoke instances that
                  are each able to set their own community standards and rules;
                  Threads, adopting Mastodon technology for a Twitter-style
                  platform under the auspices of Meta (and with the corporate
                  baggage that this entails); and Bluesky, another federatable
                  but to date more centralised platform whose corporate
                  structure is intended to prevent a Musk-style take-over by
                  hostile and autocratic techbros. This effort to replace
                  Twitter with something else that looks and feels almost
                  exactly like Twitter, just without the stench of Musk, both
                  demonstrates the extent to which ‘old’ Twitter in its style,
                  functionality, and affordances for public debate had captured
                  the attention of social media users, and betrays a lack of
                  imagination about what better alternatives could look like. As
                  Christianna Silva wrote in a perceptive Mashable article, “the
                  same type of guy keeps making the same social media platforms
                  and I am tired” (Silva) – a sentiment that, given Twitter
                  founder Jack Dorsey’s early involvement in Bluesky, could even
                  be shortened to ‘the same guy keeps making the same platform’.
                  If, as she suggests, “the solution to Twitter's downfall isn’t
                  five Twitter clones”, but something new that genuinely
                  improves on the user experience of Twitter and comparable
                  platforms, what might this entail? This question assumes,
                  first, that in spite of the move towards richer and more
                  immersive multimedia formats (with platforms like Instagram
                  and TikTok) there remains a demand and purpose for
                  text-centric social media platforms like Twitter. In addition,
                  other distinct aspects of Twitter – such as the flat, open,
                  and not necessarily reciprocal nature of its network, which
                  enables a considerably greater presence of weak-tie
                  connections – also contribute to its unique user experience,
                  and encourage the platform’s use for predominantly public
                  connection and discussion, including but not limited to
                  journalistic purposes. These should also be retained. Indeed,
                  it is notable that these features are amongst those most
                  faithfully replicated by Mastodon, Threads, or Bluesky; the
                  emergence of third-party tools to transfer users’ established
                  Twitter networks of followers and followees to these new
                  spaces clearly also speaks to a continuing user interest in
                  such aspects. A text-centric, weak-tie, predominantly public
                  platform still fills a unique niche in the social media
                  ecosystem that has been vacated with the death of Twitter,
                  then. Any new platforms seeking to replace Twitter will be
                  subject to the same attempts to disrupt and suppress genuine
                  public debate that old Twitter was, however; they must be
                  better prepared for this. This is unlikely for Threads, which
                  is compromised by parent company Meta’s inconstant and
                  politically expedient commitment to protecting users from
                  abuse and disinformation. It is complicated for Mastodon,
                  where such efforts are at the discretion of each instance
                  operator, most of whom are amateur enthusiasts with strictly
                  limited resources. And it is already proving controversial for
                  Bluesky, whose approach to platform moderation is as yet not
                  fully formed (Perez, “Bluesky”). These new platforms’
                  inability to address questions of community standards and
                  moderation as an integral part of the platform design is
                  perhaps unsurprising given the long history of insufficient
                  content moderation policies on mainstream social media
                  platforms. But it also constitutes a significant missed
                  opportunity. Any platform that commits to effective and
                  consistent moderation and embeds this deeply into its
                  operations may well find this to be a significant selling
                  point for prospective new users seeking to escape the meltdown
                  of meaningful public debate on Twitter and elsewhere. Indeed,
                  what the early years of Twitter showed most clearly is that
                  the platform was most successful when it worked closely with
                  its users, when it listened to their needs and wishes, when it
                  incorporated user innovations like retweets, hashtags, and
                  search functions into the platform infrastructure proper, and
                  when it enabled third-party developers to build powerful new
                  functionality around that infrastructure by providing a
                  well-documented Application Programming Interface (API).
                  Emerging platforms show at least some signs that they have
                  learnt from this. So far, Bluesky’s own API is powerful and
                  wide open to potential users. Mastodon’s federated structure
                  might be understood as a distributed experiment to explore a
                  variety of approaches to working with users, some of which
                  will succeed while others will fail. Both operate on shared
                  and extensible protocol frameworks for building social media
                  platforms that encourage third-party experimentation. Any such
                  openness may also be targeted by reactionary groups seeking to
                  undermine the potential prosocial uses of these platforms,
                  however, and the central challenge to the platform operators
                  will be how to prepare for and respond to such attempts when
                  (not if) they are made. Will they naïvely take the same
                  laissez-faire, ‘free speech absolutist’ approach as their
                  predecessors, even as large parts of the user community itself
                  encourage them to crack down on abuse? Will they continue to
                  platform disinformation, abuse, and hate because real action
                  against prominent problematic accounts might result in
                  political or commercial consequences? Alternatively, can they
                  develop policies that balance free speech and freedom from
                  harmful speech, and implement them fairly and consistently?
                  Can they find ways to genuinely engage and consult their
                  communities in decisions that affect the running of the
                  platform? A Difficult Path Ahead The historical trajectory of
                  Twitter over these past twenty years, and of social media and
                  their predecessor channels over an even longer period, has
                  made it abundantly clear that any prosocial public debate that
                  is genuinely open to more than the entrenched elites of the
                  Habermasian public sphere will be targeted by those who seek
                  to defend their own public influence and agenda-setting power
                  from being scrutinised and diluted, and instrumentalised by
                  those who see an opportunity to misdirect and derail public
                  discourse for their own benefit. For now, this has severely
                  curtailed the genuine potential that spaces for online public
                  debate like Twitter once showed (even in spite of their now
                  obvious flaws). This decline has occurred at a time when
                  traditional arenas for public debate – such as commercial and
                  public-service mainstream media channels – are themselves
                  severely threatened by failing business models, corporate
                  hollowing-out, journalistic self-censorship, and political
                  obstruction. In combination, the struggles of both social and
                  mainstream media have aided the current global democratic
                  backsliding towards autocracy. And yet, all hope is not lost.
                  From Belarus to Brazil, from the United States to Hungary,
                  clearly communities and societies around the world continue to
                  resist the autocratic transformation of once democratic
                  systems, and in doing so also continue to experiment with new
                  forms and platforms for public communication and debate. As
                  Twitter, now X, fades into irrelevance as a far-right fringe
                  platform overrun by AI slop and performative Musk worship, the
                  social media landscape is more diverse and fragmented than it
                  has been for many years. That fragmentation also presents a
                  considerable opportunity to explore and test platform models
                  and configurations that constitute a genuine departure and
                  avoid the mere replacement of Twitter with yet another Twitter
                  clone. Those new entrants into the social media space that
                  proactively address these challenges in the most innovative
                  way are likely to be those that will win out in the end.
